<p><a href="/wiki/Loyola_College_in_Maryland" title="Loyola College in Maryland">Loyola College in Maryland</a> <a href="/wiki/Economics" title="Economics">Economics</a> professor Thomas DiLorenzo has criticized <i>Fast Food Nation</i> for denying <a href="/w/index.php?title=Individual_responsibility&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Individual responsibility (page does not exist)">individual responsibility</a>. He further criticizes Schlosser's claims on the grounds that they are already well-known and compares them to the well-known fact that <a href="/wiki/Cigarettes" title="Cigarettes" class="mw-redirect">cigarettes</a> are bad for one's health. DiLorenzo also claims that Schlosser ignores the fact that fast food restaurants are introducing healthier options and calls the book an "one of the most boring uninformed attacks on the free market in the food industry."<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8" title=""><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup> <a name="Editions" id="Editions"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Fast_Food_Nation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Editions">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Editions</span></h2>
